# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crosby-field
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:crosby-field/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:crosby-field/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:crosby-field/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Allied Chemical was included in the Dow Jones Industrial Average since 1925.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The General Chemical Corporation commenced business on March 1, 1899.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The preferred stock of the new company was issued for tangible assets, appraised carefully over a period of nine months.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The common stock with some exceptions was issued for good-will and intangible assets and was set equal to ten years worth of earnings of each predecessor company, interpolated from 5.5 years of earnings reports.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The appraisal was $14,008,955 of aggregate capital and the total capital invested in the United States in chemical works was estimated to have been $238,000,000 in 1899.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Incorporated as the *American Coal Products Co.* and before May 1, 1903 acquired 90% of the stock of *United Coke & Gas Co.* (a producer of byproduct coke ovens ) and 80% of *Barrett Manufacturing Co.* of West Virginia (a producer of various coal products).
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] On January 1, 1909, sold its coke oven interests (which included the *United Otto* and *Otto Hoffman* coke oven patents) to the *Oberschlesische Kokswerke & Chemische Fabriken AG* of Berlin, which formed the *German-American Coke & Gas Co.* in which American Coal Products Co. had some interest.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Renamed to (The) Barrett Co. on January 25, 1916.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] During World War I, Imperial Germany controlled much of the world's chemical production.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] This resulted in critical shortages of certain dyes, drugs and especially ammonia, a vital compound used to make fertilizers and explosives.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] In 1920, publisher Eugene Meyer and noted chemist William Henry Nichols founded Allied Chemical and Dye Corporation in order to address this shortcoming in American industrial production.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Allied was an amalgamation of five existing companies with a total capitalization of $175,000,000, including Barrett Chemical Company (est.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] 1858), The General Chemical Company (est.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] 1899), National Aniline & Chemical Company (est.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] 1895), and the Solvay Process Company (est.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] All manufacturing was consolidated in Buffalo, and much attention was given to improving the processes hastily introduced during World War I.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Allied's first venture into new markets was the construction of a synthetic ammonia plant near Hopewell, Virginia in 1928.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] This would soon become the world's largest producer of ammonia.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Pursuant to a plan adopted September 9, 1920, stockholders of the companies to be consolidated were invited to deposit their stock for exchange.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] By December 2, 1920, well above 90% were deposited, the exchange offer expired December 15 and on December 17, 1920 the new company was incorporated in the state of New York.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Stock certificates began trading on the New York Stock Exchange in September.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Barrett (since 1916), National Aniline (since 1919) and General Chemical (since 1902) were listed on the NYSE at the time of merger, the two Solvay companies were not.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] National Aniline and Chemical Works had been formed in 1917 by the merger of Schoellkopf Aniline and Chemical, Beckers Aniline and Chemical of Brooklyn, and the Benzol Products Company.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Included also were certain facilities of Semet-Solvay, the Barrett Company, and the General Chemical company that made coal tar intermediates.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Henry Francis Atherton joined as Secretary of the National Aniline and Chemical Company in the 1920s and served as president of Allied Chemical and Dye Corporation from 1934 to 1946.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] He was also chairman of the board from 1935, until his death in 1949.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The company was renamed to *Allied Chemical Corporation* on April 28, 1958.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] After World War II, Allied began manufacturing other products, including Nylon 6, refrigerants and plastic dinnerware.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The company name was simplified to reflect thithumbsAllied Chemical flatware, creamer, coffee cup diversification, becoming Allied Chemical Corporation in 1958.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] It also moved its headquarters to Morristown, New Jersey.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] In 1962, Allied bought Union Texas Natural Gas.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Allied initially regarded Union as a vertical integration supplier of raw materials for its chemical products.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Connor, secretary of commerce under president Lyndon Johnson, sold many of Allied's unprofitable businesses in the 1970s and invested more heavily in oil and gas exploration.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] By 1979, Union Texas was generating 80% of Allied's revenue.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Between 1978 and 1979, Allied funded *The MacNeil/Lehrer Report* on public television.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] As the company sought to further diversify its operations, it was renamed Allied Corporation in 1981.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Its next acquisition, in 1983, was Bendix Corporation, an aerospace and automotive firm.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] By 1984, Bendix was generating 50% of Allied's income, while oil and gas generated 38%.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] Between 1964 and 1984, the reporting marks used to identify Allied Chemical's rolling stock on the North American railroad network was *NLX*.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] At one point in 1985, Allied funded *Nova* on PBS.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] In 1985, Allied merged with the Signal Companies to become AlliedSignal.
[src:crosby-field/allied-corp] The company would eventually acquire Honeywell in 1999, and adopt its name.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:crosby-field/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The **American Institute of Chemical Engineers** (**AIChE**) is a professional organization for chemical engineers.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE was established in 1908 to distinguish chemical engineers as professionals independent of chemists and mechanical engineers.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] By 2024, AIChE had over 60,000 members from over 110 countries (sources vary).
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] There are over 350 active student chapters at universities worldwide.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Student chapters aim to provide networking opportunities in academia and industry as well as increase student involvement locally and nationally.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] This section consists of excerpts from a historical pamphlet written for the Silver Anniversary of the AICHE in 1932.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] In 1905, *The Chemical Engineer* rounded out its first year of publication with an editorial by its founder and prominent engineer, Richard K.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meade, that propounded the question: "Why not the American Society of Chemical Engineers?" He went on to say: "The profession is now a recognized one and there are probably at least five hundred chemical engineers in this country".
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mechanical, civil, electrical, and mining engineers in the United States each had already established a national society, so Meade's editorial was quite pertinent.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] But it took time for the idea to take root and Meade kept promoting it for the next two years.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Finally, in 1907, he issued a call for a preliminary meeting to be held in Atlantic City in June 1907.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Some early leaders of the profession, Charles F.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler, and Thorn Smith along with about a dozen others answered Meade's call and met in Atlantic City on June 21, 1907.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The meeting concluded with the formation of an organizing committee of six members: Charles F.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee sent a letter in September 1908 to 600 men in the chemical profession in the United States and Canada asking for their opinions about forming a chemical engineering society.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Two hundred replies were received and 70-80% were favorable.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Many of the others believed the existing societies (especially the American Chemical Society) were sufficient and they did not favor forming a new society.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee decided to hold a larger, open meeting at the Hotel Belmont in New York City at which those opposed to forming the new society could present their arguments and opinions.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Accordingly, they invited fifty men prominent in the chemical profession (including men who opposed the forming of a new society) to meet on January 18, 1908.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Twenty-one men attended the meeting and fourteen others expressed their views in letters.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] After much discussion, the meeting ended without reaching a definitive decision.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] However, it was agreed to have a mail vote (on whether or not to form a chemical engineering society) after a complete stenographic report of the meeting was printed and sent to the fifty men who had been invited to the meeting.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mail vote resulted in 36 replies of which 22 were in the affirmative, 6 were negative, and 8 were neutral.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Based on those voting results, the organizing committee of six called for a full-fledged organizational meeting to be held in Philadelphia on June 22, 1908.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meanwhile, the committee of six drafted a proposed constitution to be presented at that meeting.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] That meeting resulted in the official formation of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers, the adoption of a constitution, and the election of Samuel P.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler as the first president of the Institute.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Divisions and forums provide technical information, programming for AIChE's technical meetings, and awards and recognition to outstanding chemical engineers in their areas of expertise.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] They also provide opportunities for affiliation with top engineers in the general disciplines as well as in emerging fields like biotechnology and sustainability.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The prerequisite qualifications for election to any of the membership grades are available in the AIChE Bylaws.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] As new technology is developed, there is a need for experts to collaborate to achieve common goals.
[src:crosby-field/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE plays a major role through joint initiatives with industry, academia, and others.
[src:crosby-field/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:crosby-field/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:crosby-field/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:crosby-field/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] Field was born in Jamestown, New York, in 1889 as only child.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] After his graduation in 1912 Field had started working at General Electric, among others at the Protective Apparatus Laboratory under Charles Proteus Steinmetz.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] After making a start with his own private practice as consulting engineer in 1914-15, he became chief engineer at Standard Aniline Products Corporation, now part of Allied Corp.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] After the outbreak of World War I, he served as in the United States Army Ordnance Department as inspector in ordnance, in which he rose to major.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] After World War I he returned to chemical industry as engineering manager of the National Aniline and Chemical Works, which would also merge into Allied Corp.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] In 1923 he to the Brillo Manufacturing Company, where he eventually served as vice president until 1942.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] In World War II Fields again served in the US ARMY Ordnance Corps in the rank as colonel and assistant director of safety in the Office of the Chief of Ordnance.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] Field was elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and was awarded the ASME Medal in 1953.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] He served as president of the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE), and on the council of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers.
[src:crosby-field/crosby-field] Over the years he had obtained more than 140 patents.
